         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Mt. Macedon ¶ 3/12/83. ¶  ¶ Merely a few lines from this locality, dear Sir Joseph, where I have gone to seek restoration of my health. Since about 3 months I suffer from a severe Bronchial catarrh; t...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.12.03</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, f. 73.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation 'And JDH'.</p>
               </note>Mt. Macedon<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Vic.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">3/12/83.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Merely a few lines from this locality, dear Sir Joseph, where I have gone to seek restoration of my health. Since about 3 months I suffer from a severe Bronchial catarrh; there is some emphysema and thickening of the mucous membranes. As the hot weather sets in, I <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">may</hi>
               </seg> recover; but with my hereditary disposition to Phthisis it is doubtful. Since I left the garden, I had to live, poor as I am and heavily taxed, in small unhealthy Officerooms, and I did no longer get the invigorating daily exercises, which I had in the garden, to preserve my health.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have written an article here for Uhlworm &amp; Behrens "bot. Central-Blatt,"<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B84.04.05.</p>
               </note> vindicating Bentham's and your authority-rights, to the species which you from one genus to an other (indicated as) transposed, a right which by A.D.C. latest brochure<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A. de Candolle (1883).</p>
               </note> is called into question.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This locality is poor in plants; nor dare I go far, as the exertion would chill the air-passages notwithstanding a respirator. I noticed however here for the first time <name key="Centunculus%20minimus">Centunculus minimus</name>, altho' Prof. Tate had it recently also from one place in S.A.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to R. Tate, 1 December 1883 (in this edition as 83-12-01a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope Mr Bentham, after some mental rest, will feel revigorated again as the spring sets in with you. Chevreul is still active at 97, so B. ought to cheer up. When you see the venerable Gentleman, give him the expression of my best wishes for his recovery</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">The person, who styles himself Director here,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William Guilfoyle.</p>
               </note> reported recently to the Government here, and to the press,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 24 October 1883.</p>
               </note> that <name key="Bromus%20sterilis">Bromus sterilis</name> was a native of America and highly valuable as a fodder grass!<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For M's response, see M to G. Berry, 24 October 1883, published in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 26 October 1883, p. 7. The species is a native of Europe and western Asia and, according to M, was generally regarded as a pest rather than as valuable for fodder.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bromus%20sterilis">Bromus sterilis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Centunculus%20minimus">Centunculus minimus</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
